The statement that all Fermat numbers F_n = 2^{2^n} + 1 are prime is false. For n = 5, F_5 = 2^{32} + 1 = 4294967297, which is composite because it is divisible by 641 (4294967297 ÷ 641 = 6700417).

Fermat numbers are prime for n = 0 to 4, but not for n = 5 and beyond for some values of n. The conjecture that all Fermat numbers are prime is disproven by the counterexample of F_5.

\boxed{\text{The statement is false because } F_5 = 2^{32} + 1 = 4294967297 \text{ is divisible by } 641 \text{ and hence composite.}}
